### Interface Satisfaction

A type satisfies an interface if it implements all the interface's methods.

### Implicit Satisfaction

```go
type Speaker interface {
    Speak() string
}

type Dog struct{}
func (d Dog) Speak() string { return "Woof!" }

type Cat struct{}
func (c Cat) Speak() string { return "Meow!" }

type Robot struct{}
func (r Robot) Speak() string { return "Beep boop" }

// All three types satisfy Speaker implicitly
var speakers []Speaker = []Speaker{Dog{}, Cat{}, Robot{}}
```

### Compile-Time Check

To verify satisfaction at compile time:

```go
type MyWriter struct{}
func (m MyWriter) Write(p []byte) (n int, err error) {
    return len(p), nil
}

// Compile-time check
var _ io.Writer = (*MyWriter)(nil)
```

### Interface Embedding

```go
type Reader interface {
    Read(p []byte) (n int, err error)
}

type Closer interface {
    Close() error
}

type ReadCloser interface {
    Reader
    Closer
}

// A type must have ALL methods from all embedded interfaces
```

### Pointer vs Value Receiver

```go
type Incrementer interface {
    Increment()
}

type Counter struct {
    Value int
}

// Method with pointer receiver
func (c *Counter) Increment() {
    c.Value++
}

var inc Incrementer
// inc = Counter{} // ERROR: Counter does not implement Incrementer
inc = &Counter{}     // OK: *Counter implements Incrementer
```

### Checking Satisfaction

```go
var v any = "hello"

if s, ok := v.(fmt.Stringer); ok {
    fmt.Println("implements Stringer:", s.String())
}
```

> **Key Point:** If a method uses a pointer receiver, only the pointer type satisfies the interface. For value receivers, both value and pointer types satisfy it.

codeExample:
package main

import "fmt"

type Greeter interface {
    Greet() string
}

type English struct{}
func (e English) Greet() string { return "Hello" }

type Spanish struct{}
func (s Spanish) Greet() string { return "Hola" }

type French struct{}
func (f French) Greet() string { return "Bonjour" }

// Compile-time check
var _ Greeter = (*English)(nil)

func main() {
    greeters := []Greeter{English{}, Spanish{}, French{}}
    for _, g := range greeters {
        fmt.Println(g.Greet())
    }
}
